{{US-historian-stub}}

The [[Serbs]] trace their history to the 6th and 7th-century southwards migration of Slavs. The Serbs, as the other [[South Slavs]], absorbed [[Prehistory of Southeastern Europe|Paleo-Balkan peoples]] and established various states throughout the [[Middle Ages]]; Serbian historiography agrees on that the beginning of [[Serbian history]] started with the forming of Serbian statehood in the [[Early Middle Ages]].
In the 19th century, various scholars provided several theories about the origin of the Serb ethnonym. Some researchers claimed that the ethnonym, and thereby ethnic origin, dated to ancient history. The theories are based on the presumed connection to various Roman-era ethnonyms (tribes) and toponyms. These theories remain largely unproved and controversial.
==Early historical records of the Serb name== [[Image:Map of Colchis, Iberia, Albania, and the neighbouring countries ca 1770.jpg|thumb|200px|''"Serbi"'' located near the mouth of the Volga, based on Greek literary sources, in a map printed in LONDON, ''ca'' 1770]] Various authors mentioned names of [[Serbs]] ({{lang-sr|Srbi}} / Срби) and [[Sorbs]] ([[Upper Sorbian language|Upper Sorbian]]: ''Serbja''; [[Lower Sorbian language|Lower Sorbian]]: ''Serby'') in different variants: Surbii, Suurbi, Serbloi, Zeriuani, Sorabi, Surben, Sarbi, Serbii, Serboi, Zirbi, Surbi, Sorben,{{sfn|Petković|1926|p=9}} etc. These authors used these names to refer to Serbs and Sorbs in areas where their historical (or current) presence was/is not disputed (notably in the [[Balkans]] and [[Lusatia]]), but there are also sources that mention the same or similar names in other parts of the World (most notably in the Asiatic [[Sarmatia]] in the [[Caucasus]]). Attempts of various researchers to connect these names with modern Serbs produced various theories about the origin of the Serb people.
;Early historical mentions of an alleged "Serb" ethnonym in the Caucasus: *[[Pliny the Younger]] in his work ''Plinii Caecilii Secundi Historia naturalis'' from the first century AD (69-75) mentioned people named [[Serboi|Serbi]],<ref name="Aleksandar M. Petrović 2006, page 19">Aleksandar M. Petrović, Arheografija naroda jugoistočne Evrope, Beograd, 2006, page 19.</ref> who lived near the [[Cimmerians]], presumably on the [[Black Sea]] and the [[Sea of Azov]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2015}} *In the 2nd century (around 175 AD), the [[Egypt]]ian [[Greek people|Greek]] scientist [[Claudius Ptolemy]] mentioned in his ''[[Geography (Ptolemy)|Geography]]'' people named [[Serboi|Serboi or Sirboi]],<ref name="Aleksandar M. Petrović 2006, page 19"/> who presumably lived behind the [[Caucasus]], in the hinterland of the [[Caspian Sea]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2015}}
;Early historical mentions of other Serb-sounding names that some researchers are trying to connect with the Serb people: *In the same book where he mentioned people named [[Serboi]], [[Claudius Ptolemy]] also mentioned city named [[Serbinum]] in [[Pannonia]].<ref name="Aleksandar M. Petrović 2006, page 19"/> *Ancient geographer [[Strabo]] mentioned that river [[Xanthos]] in [[Lycia]] was formerly named [[Sirbis]].<ref>Aleksandar M. Petrović, Arheografija naroda jugoistočne Evrope, Beograd, 2006, page 20.</ref> *[[Herodotus]] mentions lake named [[Serbonis]] in [[Egypt]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2015}} This lake was also mentioned as [[Sirbonis]] by [[Strabo]].{{sfn|Petković|1926|pp=18–19}} *In the 10th century, [[Byzantine emperor]] [[Constantine VII Porphyrogennetos]] (912-959) mentioned in his book [[De Ceremoniis]], apart from the Slavic [[Croats]] and Serbs, there were two tribes named Krevatades (Krevatas) and Sarban ([[Sarbani]]), which some researches identified as Croats and Serbs.{{citation needed|reason=Original research|date=March 2015}} These tribes were located in the [[Caucasus]] near the river [[Terek River|Terek]], between [[Alania]] and [[Tsanaria]].<ref>[https://books.google.rs/books?id=CX4fAAAAIAAJ&q=krevatades+sarban De administrando imperio, Constantine VII Porphyrogenitus (Emperor of the East), Gyula Moravcsik, Pázmány Péter Tudományegyetemi Görög Filológiai Intézet, 1949, page 115.]</ref><ref name="books.google.com">[https://books.google.com/books?ei=ks67TqHhPMqnhAeziPDPBw&ct=result&hl=sr&id=BLhtAAAAMAAJ&dq=krevatas+sarban&q=sarban#search_anchor Parameśa Caudhurī, India in Kurdistan, Qwality Book Company, 2005, page 79.]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=aKEaAAAAIAAJ&q=krevatas+sarban&dq=krevatas+sarban&hl=sr&ei=Qf67Ts2YEcSD4gTrpbBA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAQ The Slavs: their early history and civilization, Francis Dvornik, American Academy of Arts and Sciences, 1959, page 28.]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=zqHGOC2GIHgC&pg=PA397 Constantini Porphyrogenneti... libri duo De ceremoniis aulæ Byzantinæ. Prodeunt nunc primum Græce, cum Latina interpretatione et commentariis. Curarunt Io. Henricus Leichius et Io. Iacobus Reiskius..., VII Constantin, Gleditschius, 1754, page 397.]</ref> The Sarban tribe in the Caucasus in the 10th century was also recorded by an [[Arab]] geographer.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=YbS9QmwDC58C&pg=PA56&dq=sarban+masudi&hl=sr&ei=E-S_TtOzG9CHhQeFuezABA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CEIQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=sarban&f=false The early medieval Balkans: a critical survey from the sixth to the late twelfth century, John Van Antwerp Fine, University of Michigan Press, 1991, page 56.]</ref>
<gallery> Image:Tabula Asiae II - Sarmatia Asiatica.jpg|People with name ''Sirbi'' near the estuary of the river [[Volga]], on Ptolemaic map from 1552. Image:Ptolemaic map Scythia 1598.jpg|People with name ''Sirbi'' near the estuary of the river [[Volga]], on Ptolemaic map from 1598. Image:European and Asiatic Sarmatia 1794.JPG|People with name Serbi (Серби) near the estuary of the river [[Volga]], according to the map from the book of Jovan Rajić, printed in Vienna in 1794. </gallery>
==Migration of White Serbs to the Balkans== [[Image:White serbia white croatia01.png|thumb|200px|Locations of White Serbia and White Croatia in the 6th century (around 560), according to the book of Francis Dvornik.]] [[Image:Dervan.png|thumb|200px|[[Dervan]]'s Serbia (White Serbia), 7th century.]] [[Image:Serb lands in the 9th century (en).png|thumb|200px|Serb lands in the [[Balkans]] in the 9th century, mostly according to [[De Administrando Imperio]].]] According to ''[[De Administrando Imperio]]'' ({{abbreviation|DAI|De Administrando Imperio}}, written by the [[Byzantine emperor]] [[Constantine VII]] (912-959), the Serbs originated from the "[[White Serbs]]" who lived on the "other side of Turkey" (name used for [[Hungary]]), in the area that they called "Boiki". White Serbia bordered to the Franks and [[White Croatia]]. DAI claims that after two brothers inherited the rule from their father, one of them took half of the people and migrated to the [[Byzantine Empire]] (i.e. to the [[Balkans]]), which was governed by Emperor [[Heraclius]] (610-641).<ref>Sava S. Vujić - Bogdan M. Basarić, Severni Srbi (ne)zaboravljeni narod, Beograd, 1998, pages 38-39.</ref>{{sfn|Petrović|1997|pp=90-91}}<ref>Vladimir Ćorović, Ilustrovana istorija Srba, knjiga prva, Beograd, 2005, page 61.</ref> According to German historian L. A. Gebhardi, the two brothers were sons of [[Dervan]], the ''dux'' (duke) of the [[Sorbs (tribe)|Surbi (Sorbs)]].<ref>Sava S. Vujić - Bogdan M. Basarić, Severni Srbi (ne)zaboravljeni narod, Beograd, 1998, page 40.</ref>
In the [[Balkans]], [[Serbs]] settled first around rivers [[Tara (Drina)|Tara]], [[Ibar (river)|Ibar]], [[Drina]] and [[Lim (river)|Lim]] (in the present-day border region of [[Serbia]], [[Montenegro]] and [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], but also [[Dalmatia]]), and joined with surrounding [[South Slavs|South Slavic]] tribes that came to the Balkans earlier (in the 6th century) and the Paleo-Balkan people. Over time, the South Slavic and mostly Illyrian tribes of this territory mixed with the Serbs and also adopted Serb name as their own.<ref name="Sava S 1998, page 36">Sava S. Vujić - Bogdan M. Basarić, Severni Srbi (ne)zaboravljeni narod, Beograd, 1998, page 36.</ref>
Another part of the White Serbs did not migrate southwards, but remained in the [[Elbe]] region. Descendants of these White Serbs are the present day Lusatian Serbs ([[Sorbs]]), who still live in the [[Lusatia]] (Lužica, Lausitz) region of eastern [[Germany]].
There are also opinions that data from "De administrando imperio" that describes Serb migration to the Balkans is not correct and that Serbs came to the Balkans from [[East Slavs|Eastern Slavic]] lands, together with other [[South Slavs]].{{sfn|Novaković|1992|p=57}}<ref>Nikola Jeremić, Srpska zemlja Bojka, Zemun, 1993, page 33.</ref>
The Emperor [[Constantine III (Byzantine emperor)|Constantine III]] (641) transferred a part of the [[Slavs]] from the [[Balkans]] ([[Vardar]] region) to [[Asia Minor]]. There these migrants founded the city of [[Gordoservon]], the name of which gives grounds for supposing that among its founders there were [[Serbs]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=K5hpAAAAMAAJ&q=gordoservon&dq=gordoservon&hl=sr&ei=d_G-Tpn7OomZhQfS16WuBA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CEMQ6AEwBTgK The Macedonian question: the struggle for southern Serbia, Đoko M. Slijepčević, American Institute for Balkan Affairs, 1958, page 50.]</ref> The city was also known under names Gordoserbon and Servochoria.
==Theories==
===Iranian theory=== Theory about [[Iranian peoples|Iranian]] origin of the Serb ethnonym assumes that ancient [[Serboi|Serbi / Serboi]] from north [[Caucasus]] (Asiatic Sarmatia) were a [[Sarmatians|Sarmatian]] ([[Alans|Alanian]]) tribe.<ref name="Miodrag Milanović 2008, page 81">Miodrag Milanović, Srpski stari vek, Beograd, 2008, page 81.</ref> The theory subsequently assumes that Alanian Serbi were subdued by the [[Huns]] in the 4th century and that they, as part of the Hunnic army, migrated to the western edge of the [[Huns#Unified Empire under Attila|Hunnic Empire]] (in the area of [[Central Europe]] near the river [[Elbe]], later designated as [[White Serbia]] in what is now [[Saxony]] (eastern [[Germany]]) and western [[Poland]]). After the Hunnic leader [[Attila]] died (in 453), Alanian Serbi presumably became independent and ruled in the east of the river [[Saale]] (in modern-day [[Germany]]) over the local [[Slavs|Slavic]] population.<ref name="Miodrag Milanović 2008, page 81"/>{{sfn|Novaković|1992|p=46}} Over time, they, it is argued, intermarried with the local [[Slavs|Slavic population]] of the region,<ref name="Miodrag Milanović 2008, page 81"/>{{sfn|Novaković|1992|p=46}} adopted Slavic language, and transferred their name to the Slavs.{{sfn|Novaković|1992|p=48}} According to [[Tadeuš Sulimirski]], similar event could occur in the [[Balkans]] or [[Serbs]] who settled in the Balkans were Slavs who came from the north and who were ruled by already slavicized [[Alans]].{{sfn|Novaković|1992|p=46}}
[[Image:Migrations serbes avant 1000.png|thumb|200px|left|Hypothetical Serb migration from Sarmatia]] Deformed human skulls that are connected to the Alans are also discovered in the area that was later designated as "White Serbia".{{sfn|Novaković|1992|p=48}} According to Indo-European interpretation, different sides of the [[World]] are designated with different colors, thus, white color is designation for the west, black color for the north, blue or green color for the east and red color for the south. According to that view, [[White Serbia]] and [[White Croatia]] were designated as western Serbia and western Croatia, and were situated in the west from some hypothetical lands that had same names and that presumably existed in the east.<ref>Relja Novaković, Srbi, Zemun, 1993, page 61.</ref>
It is possible that the Alanian Serbi in Sarmatia, similarly like other Sarmatian/Iranian peoples on the northern Caucasus, originally spoke an Indo-European [[Iranian languages|Iranian]] language similar to present-day [[Ossetian language|Ossetian]]. The Ossetian language is a member of [[Iranian languages|Eastern Iranian]] branch of Iranian languages, along with [[Pashto language|Pashtun]], [[Yaghnobi language|Yaghnobi]] and languages of the [[Pamir languages|Pamir]]. One of the [[Pashtuns|Pashtun]] tribal groups in [[Afghanistan]] and [[Pakistan]] is known as [[Sarbans]] (Sarbani) and Pashtuns are believed to be of [[Scythian]] descent while their language is classified as East Scythian (Sarmatian language is also grouped within Scythian branch).
In [[Poland|Polish]] history, the Polish nobility claimed to be direct descendants of the historic [[Sarmatian]] people (see: [[Sarmatism]]) and this might be connected with historical [[White Serbia]] and [[White Croatia]], which included parts of present-day [[Poland]]. {{Citation needed|date=January 2013}}
===Autochthonic theory=== This theory assumes that Serbs are an [[autochthon (person)|autochthon]]ic people in the [[Balkans]] and [[Podunavlje]], where they presumably lived before historical Slavic and Serb migration to the Balkans in the 6th-7th centuries.{{sfn|Petrović|1997|pp=9–10}} Proponents of this theory (for example [[Jovan I. Deretić]], [[Olga Luković Pjanović]], [[Miloš Milojević]]) claimed that Serbs either came to the Balkans long before the 7th century or Serb 7th century migration to the Balkans was only partial and Serbs who, according to "[[De administrando imperio]]", came from the north founded in the Balkans other Serbs that already lived there.{{sfn|Petrović|1997|pp=9–10}} It is suggested that ancient city of [[Serbinum]] in [[Pannonia]] was named after these hypothetical autochthonic Serbs.{{sfn|Petrović|1997|p=8}}
===Proto-Slavic theory=== *[[Sporoi]] ({{lang-el|Σπόροι}}) was according to Eastern Roman scholar [[Procopius]] (500–560) the old name of the [[Antae]] and [[Sclaveni]], two [[Early Slav]]ic branches. Procopius stated that the Sclavenes and Antes [[Proto-Slavic|spoke the same language]], but did not trace their common origin back to the [[Venethi]] but to a people he called "Sporoi".<ref name=Barford-36>{{cite book|ref=harv|author=Paul M. Barford|title=The Early Slavs: Culture and Society in Early Medieval Eastern Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1Z9ItAtbJ5AC|date=January 2001|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=978-0-8014-3977-3|page=36}}</ref> He derived the name to Greek {{lang|el|σπείρω}} ("I scatter grain"), because "they populated the land with scattered settlements".<ref name=Hrushevskyi>{{cite book|author1=Михайло Грушевський|author2=Andrzej Poppe|author3=Marta Skorupsky |author4=Uliana M. Pasicznyk |author5=Frank E. Sysyn|title=History of Ukraine-Rus': From prehistory to the eleventh century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L_ENAQAAMAAJ|year=1997|publisher=Kiyc Cius|isbn=978-1-895571-19-6|page=57}}</ref> According to Bohemian historian [[Josef Dobrovský]] (1753–1829) and Slovak historian [[Pavel Jozef Šafárik]] (1795–1861) it was a corruption of ''Srbi'' ([[Serbs]]).<ref>{{harvnb|J. B. Bury|2013|p=295}}</ref> Šafárik deemed that it was the oldest generic name of the Slavs.<ref name="institute1879">{{cite book|author=Royal anthropological institute|title=The Journal of the Anthropological institute|volume=8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TqIEAAAAQAAJ|year=1879|page=66}}</ref> *In the mid-9th century the so-called [[Bavarian Geographer]] wrote that people named [[Zeriuani]] had so large kingdom that all [[Slavic peoples]] originated from there (or from them).{{sfn|Petrović|1997|p=90}}<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=OvxGAAAAIAAJ&q=zeriuani&dq=zeriuani Quaestiones medii aevi, Томови 1-4, Uniwersytet Warszawski. Instytut Historyczny, Polskie Towarzystwo Historyczne. Commission d'histoire médiévale, Éditions de l'Université de Varsovie, 1977, page 31.]</ref> According to one of interpretations, Zeriuani are identified with Serbs, and there are opinions that "Serbs" was an old name of all Slavic peoples.<ref>[[Lazo M. Kostić]], O srpskom imenu, Srbinje - Novi Sad, 2000, pages 38-39.</ref> However, according to other opinions, Zeriuani might be a name used for [[Severians]] or [[Sarmatians]] instead for Serbs.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=KUsiAQAAMAAJ&q=zeriuani&dq=zeriuani Prosvjeta, Том 16, Društvo hrvatskih književnika., 1908, page 216.]</ref>
